Module 16 – Exhibits Are Anchors, Not Extras 📎⚓

Core Message

Exhibits aren’t add-ons — they’re the weight that keeps your argument steady.

⸻

Lesson Introduction

Without exhibits, your statements are just claims. Exhibits make them verifiable facts. For a pro se litigant, labeling, referencing, and filing exhibits correctly ensures they carry maximum procedural weight.

⸻

Teaching Block

1. Label Clearly
	•	Exhibit A, B, C — with descriptive titles.
	•	Match exhibit references exactly between text and attachment.

2. Make Them Legible
	•	Ensure copies are readable and complete.
	•	Highlight key sections without altering the document.

3. Tie to Argument
	•	Reference exhibits at the precise point in your filing where they matter.

⸻

Real-World Illustration

In the arbitration case, Exhibit A (employment agreement) was referenced in multiple sections, anchoring both factual and legal arguments.

⸻

Assignment Prompt

Task:
Choose one piece of evidence and label, title, and reference it in a mock motion paragraph.

⸻

Model Answer (Sample)

“As shown in Exhibit B – July 14, 2025 Court Order, the appellate court reclassified the matter, removing appeal rights.”

⸻

Reflection Summary

Exhibits are not optional — they’re the procedural ballast.

⸻

Visual Pairing

Image Concept:
A ship anchored securely by large, labeled exhibit binders. Caption:
“Exhibits Keep Your Case in Place.”